Evaluation to remove or not Outliers using IRQ¶

In [112]:
##### Specify the columns to exclude outliers
columnsToExcludeOutliers = ['EPS', 'Liquidity', 'Profitability', 'Productivity', 'Leverage Ratio', 'Asset Turnover',
           'Operational Margin', 'Return on Equity', 'Market Book Ratio', 'Assets Growth',
           'Sales Growth', 'Employee Growth','BK']

# Imputed DataFrame after to fill missing values
myImputed_BrDF

# Create an empty DataFrame to store the filtered data
myImputedDF_excluded_IQR = pd.DataFrame()

# Set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# Iterate through each column
for col in columnsToExcludeOutliers:
    # Calculate the IQR for the current column
    Q1 = myImputed_BrDF[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = myImputed_BrDF[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    # Define the outlier boundaries index for the current column
    lower_index = Q1 - (1.5 * IQR)
    upper_index = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)

    # Filter out the outliers for the current column
    columns_filtered = myImputed_BrDF[(myImputed_BrDF[col] >= lower_index) & (myImputed_BrDF[col] <= upper_index)]
 

    # Append the filtered column to the data_filtered DataFrame
    myImputedDF_excluded_IQR[col] = columns_filtered[col]



    # Create a boxplot for the current column
    # Set the figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    plt.subplot(3, 4, columnsToExcludeOutliers.index(feature) + 1)
    sns.boxplot(y=col, data=columns_filtered)
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {col} (Outliers Excluded)')
    plt.show()

After removing the outliers from the dataset using IRQ,¶

The BK column representing bankruptcy (minority class) only contains values of 0 (majority class). This can lead to class imbalance in the data, where the dataset has a majority class (0) and no instances of the minority class (1).¶

Conclusion after to validate removing outliers¶

After to validate removing outliers, it results in the loss of all data with a value of 1 in the BK column. It is important to carefully consider the decision to remove outliers. In this case, by losing all the data with a value of 1, the model may not be able to properly learn the patterns associated with the minority class and could result in inaccurate or biased predictions towards the majority class.¶

Then I will continue using original dataframe after the imputed missing values including Outliers -> myImputed_BrDF¶

Conclusion¶

Logistic Regression:¶

  • The following conclusions may be taken based on the findings of three distinct machine learning models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and Decision Tree):

Logistic Regression (LR):

  • With a score of 0.6931, the accuracy is poor, suggesting that about 69.31% of the samples were properly identified.
  • Precision and F1-score are also relatively low. This suggests that the model has a low proportion of true positives among the positive predictions, and struggles to make accurate predictions and capture the patterns of the minority class.
  • The recall is 51.75%, indicating that the model is able to identify approximately 51.75% of the positive samples.
  • The confusion matrix shows a high number of false positives and false negatives.

Random Forest:¶

  • The accuracy is high, with a value of 0.9834, indicating that approximately 98.34% of the samples were correctly classified.
  • The precision and F1-score are low, around 11.76% and 16.26% respectively. This suggests that the model has a low proportion of true positives among the positive predictions, and struggles to make precise predictions.
  • The recall is 26.32%, indicating that the model is able to identify approximately 26.32% of the positive samples.
  • The confusion matrix shows a lower number of false positives and false negatives compared to the Logistic Regression model.

Decision Tree:¶

  • The accuracy is high, with a value of 0.9673, indicating that approximately 96.73% of the samples were correctly classified.
  • The precision and F1-score are low, around 6.82% and 11.37% respectively. This suggests that the model has a low proportion of - true positives among the positive predictions, and struggles to make precise predictions.
  • The recall is 34.21%, indicating that the model is able to identify approximately 34.21% of the positive samples.
  • The confusion matrix shows a moderate number of false positives and false negatives.
Overall, the Random Forest model demonstrates the best performance in terms of accuracy, with a high value of 0.9834. However, all models struggle to make precise predictions and have poor performance in identifying the positive samples¶

Risk Assessment:¶
  • To discover prospective high-risk investments, use the model to estimate the bankruptcy risk of individual firms or a portfolio of enterprises. ##### Credit Underwriting:
  • Incorporate the bankruptcy prediction model into the credit underwriting process to evaluate the creditworthiness of borrowers and make informed lending decisions. ##### Early Warning System:
  • Continuously monitor companies' financial indicators and periodically reapply the model to identify early warning signs of financial distress, allowing for proactive interventions or adjustments in investment strategies. ##### Portfolio Management:
  • Utilize bankruptcy predictions to manage and rebalance investment portfolios, ensuring a diversified and balanced allocation of assets with consideration for bankruptcy risk. ##### Mergers and Acquisitions:
  • Assess the financial health and bankruptcy risk of target companies during the due diligence process for mergers and acquisitions, enabling better decision-making and risk mitigation.
